1502":"1450–1502","1454–1502":"1454–1502","1454–1505":"1454–1505","1454–Female":"1454–Deceased","1454–Male":"1454–Deceased","1455–1505":"1455–1505","1470–Male":"1470–Deceased","1460–Male":"1460–Deceased","1480–1520":"1480–1520","1430–1490":"1430–1490","1431–Female":"1431–Deceased","about 1480":"about 1480","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1502":"1502","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1454":"1454","1431":"1431","1430":"1430","1519":"1519","1505":"1505","about 1450":"about 1450","Westhorpe, Suffolk, England":"Westhorpe, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England","Beswick, Lancashire, England":"Beswick, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hart","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and North German: nickname from Middle English <i>hert</i> (Old English <i>heorot</i>), Middle Low German <i>hërte</i>, <i>harte</i> ‘hart, stag’, perhaps for a quick-footed or timorous individual.","German: variant of   Hardt   1 and 2. It is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name or nickname from German and Yiddish <i>hart</i> ‘hard’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hartmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Erwin, Heinz, Helmut, Horst, Klaus, Manfred, Dieter, Dietrich, Franz.","North German and Danish: variant of   Hart   1.","German and Swiss German: from an ancient Germanic personal name composed of the elements <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. This surname is also found in the Netherlands, France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Hungary, Czechia, and some other European countries; see also below. Compare   Hartman  ."]},{"name":"Francoeur","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Jacques, Aime, Marcel, Normand, Alcide, Amie, Anselme, Cecile, Clemence, Dominique, Georges.","French:","soldier's name from <i>franc coeur</i> ‘sincere heart’."]},{"name":"Hartin","meanings":["Irish (Donegal): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hArtáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Artán</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>Art</i>, a byname meaning ‘bear’ or ‘hero’. Compare   Hart   8.","English: habitational name from Harting (Sussex), from the Old English personal name <i>Heort</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>."]},{"name":"Hartel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Erna, Gunter, Kurt, Lutz, Otto.","German (also <b>Härtel</b>): from a pet form of an ancient Germanic compound personal name based on the element <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’.","French (Normandy): occupational name, a derivative of   Hart   7."]},{"name":"De Hart","meanings":["Dutch: from Middle Dutch <i>hart</i>, modern Dutch <i>hert</i> ‘deer, hart’ or <i>hart</i> ‘heart’ (see   Hart   5), with the definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’."]},{"name":"Hardt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Ernst, Erwin, Frieda, Gerhard, Gottlieb, Gunther, Hans, Heinz, Reinhold, Udo.","German: topographic name for someone who lived by woods used as pasture, from Middle High German <i>hart</i>.","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic compound personal name beginning with <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’."]},{"name":"Harten","meanings":["North German: patronymic from   Hart   1.","Dutch: patronymic from   Hart   4.","Dutch (<b>Van Harten</b>): habitational name from a place so named near Renkum, Gelderland."]},{"name":"Hartt","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Hart  ."]},{"name":"Harte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Sinead.","English and North German: variant of   Hart   1.","Dutch: variant of   Hart   4."]},{"name":"Hartjes","meanings":["Dutch: patronymic from a pet form of   Hart   4."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Hart was born in 1457, in Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, her father, Sir John Hart II, was 27 and her mother, Anne Hankeford, was 26. She married Robert Beswicke about 1480. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1519, in Beswick, Lancashire, England, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1457–1519":"1457–1519","1450–1502":"1450–1502","1454–1502":"1454–1502","1454–1505":"1454–1505","1454–Female":"1454–Surnud","1454–Male":"1454–Surnud","1455–1505":"1455–1505","1470–Male":"1470–Surnud","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1480–1520":"1480–1520","1430–1490":"1430–1490","1431–Female":"1431–Surnud","about 1480":"umbes 1480","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1502":"1502","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1454":"1454","1431":"1431","1430":"1430","1519":"1519","1505":"1505","about 1450":"umbes 1450","Westhorpe, Suffolk, England":"Westhorpe, Suffolk, Inglismaa, 